  "response": "Historians and biographers generally agree that Charles Darwin was not an atheist, but his religious views evolved significantly throughout his life.\n\n*   **Early Life:** Darwin was raised in a Unitarian family, and he initially intended to become a clergyman in the Church of England. He believed in a creator God.\n*   **Doubts Emerge:** During his voyage on the HMS Beagle, and particularly after the death of his daughter Annie, Darwin began to question religious dogma and the literal interpretation of the Bible. The problem of evil and suffering also troubled him.\n*   **\"Agnostic\" Leaning:** While he never explicitly declared himself an atheist, Darwin increasingly identified as an agnostic. He believed that the existence of God was unknowable. In his autobiography, he wrote that he had \"gradually come to disbelieve in Christianity as a divine revelation.\"\n*   **Pragmatic Considerations:** Darwin was cautious about expressing his religious doubts publicly, as it could have damaged his reputation and the reception of his scientific work.\n*   **Family Beliefs:** He was married to his devoutly religious cousin, Emma Wedgwood, and remained respectful of her faith.\n\nIn conclusion, while Darwin moved away from traditional religious belief, he did not fully embrace atheism. Agnosticism best describes his mature stance on the existence of God.",
